Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 106th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
The Olympics are coming to an end this weekend. What a fun couple of weeks:=
 photo-finishes, American dominance and, of course, the memes. These top at=
hletes from around the world take the stage every four years and we get to =
enjoy watching them put it all on the line. We're the real winners here =E2=
=9D=A4=EF=B8=8F. Special s/o to my high school classmate Nick Mead [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/d65ad6c1-b927-4b65-b897-cd05041f36b9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], who along with Kati=
e Ledecky, will be a flag bearer for America during the Closing Ceremony. H=
is boat won gold in the men=E2=80=99s four rowing event, bringing home gold=
 for the United States in the event for the first time in 64 years! Nick is=
 the only Olympian I know and if the rest are anything like him, then we go=
t a bunch of good people out there representing the Stars and Stripes.
There's a ton of folks with similar levels of dedication, raw horsepower, a=
nd skillfulness that don't dedicate their lives to Olympic sports. Maybe th=
ey=E2=80=99re scientists, researchers, or entrepreneurs pushing the frontie=
rs of technology and science. Fortunately, they get their own version of th=
e Olympics every Friday morning. It's called The Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) Nudge [ https://substack.com/redirect/98c34640-e0ab-4506-a208-939fe066e=
f3f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Fred Ehrsam on X
We=E2=80=99re building an ultrasound headset to enhance human experience. P=
ress a button to shift your brain state: go to sleep, boost focus, break ha=
bits, elevate mood, etc. We believe this device has the potential to improv=
e people=E2=80=99s daily lives more than any other technology.
Earlier this week, Coinbase and Paradigm founder Fred Ehrsam revealed his n=
ew company, Nudge [ https://substack.com/redirect/4aad59fb-2e6b-401a-8d67-4=
accca04e4cc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]. The company describes its future product as, =E2=80=9Can ultrasound =
headset to enhance human experience.=E2=80=9D It promises the ability to si=
mply push a button to alter your brain states, making it easier to fall asl=
eep or boost focus or break a habit.
Ultrasound technology has advanced significantly in recent years, becoming =
more precise and miniaturized. Improvements include better imaging resoluti=
on, more compact transducers, and increased safety. Given these advancement=
s, ultrasound can now be integrated into consumer devices for non-invasive =
brain stimulation and monitoring. Over the last couple of years, we=E2=80=
=99ve seen more startups take advantage of this: companies like Prophetic [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/b6ce9c25-3344-4d94-bb09-a75e48b43f0e?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] use ultrasoun=
d in its lucid-dreaming headset =E2=80=9CHalo", Butterfly IQ developed a po=
rtable ultrasound device that makes scans more accessible, and our guess is=
 that there will be a wave of ultrasound-based companies over the coming ye=
ars.
Separately, Fred=E2=80=99s story is both one worth noting and one that we h=
ope becomes less noteworthy over the coming years. Fred made a couple billi=
on dollars rethinking crypto with Coinbase and then made more money betting=
 on other crypto ventures at Paradigm=E2=80=A6all by the time he was 35 yea=
rs old. Fred is an entrepreneur with at least another 2-3 decades of horsep=
ower left in him, billions of dollars of capital, and is deciding to take o=
n important and hard challenges that can have a meaningful impact on societ=
y. Second and third time founders who got rich during the 2010s/early 2020s=
 are going to have a massive impact on the next couple of decades of techno=
logy development.=20
(2) Blood tests could soon predict your risk of Alzheimer=E2=80=99s [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/9debb9df-363f-4245-9576-f2adcc055ad1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Alison Abbott for Nature
This extraordinary turnaround in outlook for the disease that affects more =
than 55 million people worldwide comes down to two things =E2=80=94 both of=
 which were thought by many to be nigh on impossible just a decade ago. Fir=
st, drugs that can slow the disease, if it is caught early enough, are now =
coming on the market [ https://substack.com/redirect/2010fe73-1739-445c-996=
8-f64f458c5728?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ]. And second, scientists have developed relatively cheap and highly=
 accurate blood-based biomarkers for Alzheimer=E2=80=99s.
We write about Alzheimer=E2=80=99s treatment a lot here at Not Boring. It=
=E2=80=99s personal for us =E2=80=94 it runs in our family. So any time it =
comes up in the news, it naturally catches my eye. The story above is less =
about any one specific breakthrough, but how the combination of advancement=
s made in early-detection and early-treatment is impacting Alzheimer=E2=80=
=99s treatment.=20
Previously, we=E2=80=99ve covered how new drugs, when administered to early=
-onset patients, have shown efficacy in slowing the development of Alzheime=
r=E2=80=99s in patients. Eli Lilly=E2=80=99s Kisunla, for example, has been=
 proven to moderately slow cognitive decline, and could lead to patients li=
ving independently for longer periods of time.
As drugs, especially those that are more effective when administered earlie=
r in the disease=E2=80=99s development, become more ubiquitous there will b=
e an increased focus on screening and detecting Alzheimer=E2=80=99s earlier=
=2E Alzheimer=E2=80=99s prediction and det=
ection have also come along way.=20
Blood-based biomarkers like amyloid-beta and tau proteins have become accur=
ate enough for clinical use. These tests identify the presence of Alzheimer=
=E2=80=99s pathology before symptoms appear, enabling early intervention.
AI can enhance the analysis of MRI and PET scans, improving the identificat=
ion of subtle brain changes indicative of Alzheimer=E2=80=99s. These scans =
visualize amyloid plaques and tau tangles, allowing for early diagnosis. Th=
ink Ezra [ https://substack.com/redirect/572ed590-07c9-4620-924f-30a35636a3=
4b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], bu=
t for Alzheimer=E2=80=99s.
We=E2=80=99re getting early diagnosis + drugs to slow decline. Now we just =
need a treatment to knock out Alzheimer=E2=80=99s altogether.=20
(3) Achieving=C2=A0 Human=C2=A0 Level=C2=A0 Competitive=C2=A0 Robot=C2=A0 T=
able=C2=A0 Tennis [ https://substack.com/redirect/120a89fb-c232-456e-8507-e=
e748c728e59?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]
From Google DeepMind
Policy performance was assessed through 29 robot vs. human matches of which=
 the robot won 45% (13/29). All humans were unseen players and their skill =
level varied from beginner to tournament level. Whilst the robot lost all m=
atches vs. the most advanced players it won 100% matches vs. beginners and =
55% matches vs. intermediate players, demonstrating solidly amateur human-l=
evel performance.
If you=E2=80=99re anything like me, you=E2=80=99ve probably watched a few o=
f these Olympic events and thought =E2=80=94 or even, claimed to your spous=
e =E2=80=94 that =E2=80=9Cwith a few years of training, I could probably do=
 that.=E2=80=9D Shooting, equestrian events, and table tennis all come to m=
ind. Sorry to burst our bubbles here but even with a few years of training,=
 we probably couldn=E2=80=99t compete. Robots on the other hand=E2=80=A6now=
 they=E2=80=99re a different story.
Google=E2=80=99s DeepMind released the results of a recent study in which i=
ts AI robot competed against a range of table tennis players. The robot swe=
pt its human beginner opponents, went ~50/50 with intermediates, but still =
lost all of its matches vs. advanced adversaries. But with the rate of impr=
ovement in AI and robotics, I wouldn=E2=80=99t be surprised to see an Olymp=
ic-level robot pingponger by the next summer Olympics.
Despite the losses, the research was still significant in that it demonstra=
tes a robot achieving amateur human-level performance in a complex real-wor=
ld task. The robot displayed a few things: a hierarchical and modular polic=
y architecture, zero-shot sim-to-real techniques, and real-time adaptation =
to unseen opponents =E2=80=94 all major steps towards getting a robot to pe=
rform human-like tasks.
Who knows, maybe we=E2=80=99ll see one of these robots in LA in 2028.
(4) Samsung Unveils Solid-State Batteries with 20-Year Lifespan and 9-Minut=
e Charging Time [ https://substack.com/redirect/37631a7d-bd2b-4f53-850f-d35=
0ef336c25?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ]
Krishi Chowdhary TechReport
The batteries are undoubtedly fantastic. Each of them has a lifespan of aro=
und 20 years, takes only 9 minutes to charge, and can power electric vehicl=
es for up to 600 miles on a single charge.
Some electric news out of South Korea recently: Samsung revealed its newest=
 solid-state battery that has a 20 year lifespan, can power EVs for up to 6=
00 miles, and only takes 9 minutes to charge up. Mass production of these b=
atteries is planned for 2027 and the hope is that the more effective batter=
ies will drive down the costs of EVs further.
Notably, Chinese competitors already have access to similarly powerful batt=
eries. As Noah Smith recently noted, the U.S. missed the battery revolution=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/dbda9c5a-93b8-40ae-9e9e-f5f27ca1642c?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], whereas Ch=
ina has seized the lead in both battery manufacturing and development. Ther=
e are a number of reasons why China has outperformed the U.S. in batteries =
=E2=80=94 namely supply chain advantages and lack of political will in the =
U.S. =E2=80=94 but there seems to be a shift back as the U.S. realizes the =
importance of having its own battery capabilities.=20
Still, the West relies heavily on South Korean (Samsung) and Japanese (Pana=
sonic) battery production for its EVs. Samsung supplies batteries for compa=
nies like Ford, Rivian, and BMW, while Panasonic provides batteries for Tel=
sa, Toyota, and also Ford.=20
Again, we won=E2=80=99t see these specific Samsung batteries in market for =
a couple of years, but better, cheaper batteries are only going to drive do=
wn the costs and increase the utility of EVs. =20
(5) Rebuild the Arsenal [ https://substack.com/redirect/f63a807f-c22b-4658-=
a545-713664d89bce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ]
Anduril
This product is not a weapon itself, but a maker of weapons. It is a softwa=
re-defined manufacturing platform to produce advanced defense capabilities =
at hyper-scale. It has been years in the making, and it will make possible =
everything we will build in the future. We call it Arsenal.
Packy here. Yesterday, Anduril announced that it raised a $1.5 billion Seri=
es (America) F (Yeah). Along with the raise, it dropped a manufacturing man=
ifesto: Rebuild the Arsenal [ https://substack.com/redirect/f63a807f-c22b-4=
658-a545-713664d89bce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. In it, Anduril lays out its plans to build Arsenal-1, =E2=
=80=9Ca 5 million square foot state-of-the-art facility to produce autonomo=
us weapons systems.=E2=80=9D=20
The full document is worth reading to understand where Anduril believes war=
fare is heading, why we=E2=80=99re so far behind China in our ability to pr=
oduce weapons, and how the company plans to lean into America=E2=80=99s str=
engths to reboot the arsenal of democracy. As someone who read Freedom=E2=
=80=99s Forge [ https://substack.com/redirect/11896d57-4960-4346-95fe-07d2b=
93fef77?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] earlier this year, it got me fired up.=20
One thing in particular stuck out to me, in the last section on page 32. =
=E2=80=9CArsenal is founded on another idea that is diametrically opposed t=
o existing defense industry practices: Rather than geographically distribut=
ing the production of different military programs, we will seek to consolid=
ate it.=E2=80=9D Because Anduril is putting hundreds of millions of dollars=
 into the factory itself upfront, instead of trying to win government contr=
acts to build it, it can do away with the political games that sprinkle a l=
ittle bit of our supply chain in each important Congressional district. If =
it works, the government will ultimately be a funder, but putting up the ca=
sh up front to prove that there=E2=80=99s a better way is what Anduril has =
done on each of its products. Now it=E2=80=99s taking that up a level as it=
 turns=20
Disclosure: we are investors in Anduril.=20
Bonus: The case for long-term tech optimism
Abundance Institute
Topping of the week with a cool video from the Abundance Institute [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/3e39e2fb-6e16-451e-be17-8c2b578433f9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that makes the case =
for tech-optimism. Lightbulbs, bicycles, planes, cars, mobile phones, perso=
nal computers =E2=80=94  you name a technology that is ubiquitous and/or im=
portant today =E2=80=94 all faced initial challenges and pessimism. It is a=
ll part of the technology development cycle. And in the beginning part of t=
hat cycle, it=E2=80=99s easy to be pessimistic. You may even sound smart! B=
ut the long-term, optimal strategy is to be optimistic about tech.
Take today=E2=80=99s lead-off story, Nudge. It=E2=80=99s easy to jeer at. A=
 headset that shifts your brain states=E2=80=A6sounds like a crypto-billion=
aire=E2=80=99s pet project that is never going to work. And in fact, I=E2=
=80=99d bet the first couple of iterations of Nudge are pretty underwhelmin=
g. Hell, Nudge as a company may even fail. But I=E2=80=99d also be willing =
to bet that over the next ~20 years, we have affordable, effective devices =
that use ultrasound (or a similar technology) to positively impact our day-=
to-day lives.
You can sound smart today or be right in the long-term. History tells us th=
e latter is almost always the right choice. Which Steve do you want to be?
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all.
